ding Human Rights in Contemporary Chinese Fiction -- tPart 5. Beyond Universalism and Relativism -- t13. Universalism: A Particularistic Account -- t14. Dedichotomizing Discourse: Three Gorges, Two Cultures, One Nature -- tAppendix A: Universal Declaration on Human Rights -- tAppendix B: Bangkok Declaration on Human Rights -- tAppendix C: Bangkok NGO Declaration on Human Rights -- tAppendix D: Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNegotiating Culture and Human Rights provides a new interdisciplinary approach to issues of cultural values and universal human rights. Central to the discussion is the "Asian values debate," so named because of the culturally relativist ideals embraced by some key Asian governments. By analyzing how cultural difference and human rights operate in theory and practice in such areas as legal equality, women's rights, and ethnicity, the contributors forge a new way of looking at these critical issues. They call their approach "chastened universalism," arguing that respect for others' values need not lead to sterile, relativist views. Ultimately the authors conclude that it is less important to discover pre-existing common values across cultures than to create them through dialogue and debate  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDroits de l'homme (Droit international)vÉtudes transculturelles. 0aDroits de l'hommevEtudes transculturelles. 0aHuman rightsvCross-cultural studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh1 aBarnhart, Michael G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Lynda S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Lynda, eed